## Design notes

### What was added and why

| Addition | Rationale |
|---|---|
| `_mask_email()` | Reusable, testable masker — avoids repeating the masking expression at every call site |
| `_mask_cc()` | Same for card numbers; shows only the last 4 digits |
| `logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)` | Standard module-level logger; name is the module's `__name__` so callers can filter by package path |
| `try/except Exception: pass` around every `logger.*` call | Satisfies requirement 7 — a broken handler, misconfigured formatter, or encoding error in a log record can never change what the function raises or returns |

### Log-level rationale

| Level | Used for |
|---|---|
| `DEBUG` | Function entry/exit, per-item iteration, SMTP handshake steps — developer-only noise |
| `INFO` | Operations that complete successfully: order accepted, coupon applied, payment charged, email delivered |
| `WARNING` | Valid but unusual paths: unknown coupon (silently ignored), missing customer email, suppressed email send failure |
| `ERROR` | Every path that raises an exception (validation, bad card, unsupported method, payment failure) and every internal failure return (`{"success": False, …}`) |

### Sensitive data handling

- **Credit card** — `_mask_cc()` replaces digits 1–12 with `****-****-****-`, exposing only the last 4.
- **SMTP password** — `SMTP_PASS` is never passed to any logger call; a comment at the `server.login()` line makes this explicit.
- **Customer email** — `_mask_email()` is applied at every log call regardless of level (the requirement mandates masking at `DEBUG`; masking everywhere is strictly safer).

### Email exception block (`try/except/else`)

The original `except Exception: pass` is preserved exactly. The `else` clause (runs only when no exception was raised) logs the success path, keeping the warning log strictly in the failure branch — no risk of a spurious warning if the email sends cleanly.

